entry.title: [Profiles] Delete ephemeral profile when escaping local profile creation
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, when cancelling the profile customization dialog, for

instance through the escape key, it would close the dialog.



For the local profile creation case, the profile is ephemeral and not

named yet. It shouldn't be possible to escape the profile customization

in this step of the local profile creation.



Cancelling the local profile creation shouldn then close all browser

windows for the profile and thus delete it, since it's an ephemeral

profile, similar to the "Delete profile" button on the dialog.

entry.content:
All non-test code usages of this function have been removed already.

Now, this and follow-up CLs will remove the test usages, before

PDM::SetProfiles...() can be removed. This is desirable, because

PDM::SetProfiles...() relies on a hack called "enforced modifications",

which we'll be able to remove as a result. See doc linked in the bug.



SetProfiles() overwrites all existing profiles in the PDM. In most

unit tests, where no prior profiles exist, this can simply be replaced

by one or more AddProfile() calls.

entry.title: Enable -fno-math-errno for all GCC/Clang builds.
entry.content:
Math functions are allowed to set errno on failure (such as

out-of-range), or they are allowed not to; this is an implementation

detail. glibc does not, so none of our code can rely on it being

set. However, without knowing, the compiler is not allowed to substitute

an intrinsic for a math function, which means that very cheap operations

such as round-and-convert-to-int (lrintf()) become library calls

instead of single instructions. (See e.g.

https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=48139.)



Enable -fno-math-errno across all builds, since we do not need this

behavior. This makes several functions become slightly smaller;

the full Chrome binary becomes slightly larger due to more inlining

and unrolling, but e.g. content_shell on Linux loses ~15 kB .text.

Some random examples comparing before and after, across various modules

on Linux 64-bit x86:



SkMatrix::setRotate(float, float, float): 204 → 199 bytes

(calls to sinf and cosf are combined into one sincosf() call)

xnn_init_qu8_add_minmax_avx512_params.cfi: 633 → 556 bytes

(same)

blink::Color::Dark() const: 570 → 552 bytes

(call to lrintf gets replaced with cvtss2si, surrounding code

gets better due to no need to save registers for the call)

stereo_itheta: 575 → 471 bytes

(calls to sqrtf get replaced with vectorized sqrtps;

interestingly, there were already sqrtss instructions generated

in addition to the calls)

chrome_pdf::draw_utils::ShadowMatrix::ShadowMatrix(unsigned int,

double, unsigned int): 770 → 728 bytes

(the old code to take into account that the “this” pointer may

alias errno_location, since its first member is an uint32_t,

and thus reload more values from memory!)



And some examples of increases:



tflite::ops::builtin::lstm::Eval(TfLiteContext*, TfLiteNode*) [clone

.cfi]: 29165 → 32498 bytes (seems to be more unrolling)

aom_denoise_and_model_run: 25942 → 26090 bytes (replacement of

sqrt() call with sqrtsd/sqrtpd instruction makes for more

aggressive vectorization, which takes more space)



Android binary size is unchanged, for unknown reasons (perhaps Bionic

already sets this flag?). MotionMark (both on M1 and linux-perf)

is in the noise.

entry.title: [css-nesting-ident] Make {} invalid unless it's the whole value
entry.content:
To resolve some unfortunate ambiguity related to relaxed nesting

syntax, the CSSWG has decided to disallow {} from the value of

any standard property declaration unless it's the whole value [1].

Crucially, this applies even when var() is present in the value.



This CL detects these invalid braces in CSSVariableParser

by checking whether or not the top-level {} (if present) is the

only top-level component value [2].

[2] https://drafts.csswg.org/css-syntax/#component-value

entry.title: iwa: Keep track of opened response body producers
entry.content:
Short introduction:

When we read response body from a signed web bundle, the reader doesn't

need to parse it. This allows the caller of the reader to read the

response body directly from the signed web bundle file. Access to the

response body on reader side is provided by DataPipeProducer.



Before this CL the instances of the DataPipeProducer are self owned

and get deleted (and close the file) in the callback after the

reading has been completed. This means that the reader doesn't know

if the file is still being read or not.



After this CL the reader will keep track of the DataPipeProducer

instances. This allows the reader to know when the reading is

completed and the signed web bundle file may be removed

(when there are not active producers).



Besides that the web_bundle_file_data_source{.h, .cc} files were

deleted as we switch to the standard mojo::FileDataSource.

entry.title: [Gardener] Revert "[zlib] Introducing ANZAC++ hash"
entry.content:
This reverts commit e1a960f284b6f81eddb6b04eccd4f81dd07d6c95.



Reason for revert: speculative revert because inspector-protocol/overlay/overlay-with-emulation-scale.js stably fails on Linux Tests builder and this CL is most probably the culprit.



Original change's description:

> [zlib] Introducing ANZAC++ hash

>

> Since 2015 Chromium's zlib used a hardware accelerated hashing function

> (i.e. CRC32) to insert symbols in the dictionary during compression.

>

> As it was suggested by Noel Gordon, turns out that a portable hash can

> actually outperform it, yielding an average gain of 30% to 40% faster* compression while keeping similar compression ratios**.

>

> In these days, such gains are equivalent to more than 3 generations

> of silicon.

>

> The new hashing function is called ANZAC++ and can be technically

> considered a multiplicative hash (i.e. multiply-add-shift-mask).

>

> Aside being faster, it is also portable and doesn't depend on crypto

> extensions to perform (i.e. will work on RISC-V and Armv7).

>

> This patch will use ANZAC as default hashing, plus performs a huge cleanup.

>

> * Average gains: m1(31.3%), RPL_e(39.7%), RPL_p(39.4%),

> Cascade(39%), ICX(+38%), SPR(41.9%).

>

> ** Average compression ratio loss is 0.1% for the snappy data

> corpus.

entry.title: [CodeHealth] Fix leaked raw_ptr refcount in statistics recorder tests
entry.content:
This CL fixes the test which deletes a top-level StatisticsRecorder

which wasn't supposed to be destroyed. Since it may result in dangling

pointers to ranges, this CL disables releasing them in tests.



StatisticRecorder is not normally deleted and all its pointers are kept

dangling intentionally.



Histograms can be emitted from anywhere at any time (including different

threads and sequences), and a pointer to the Histogram can be cached (to

prevent lookup if emitted too frequently). It also would make the

destruction of histograms racy or would require holding some mutex lock

each time it's emitted. That's why Histogram objects are never deleted,

and BucketRange objects are not deleted as well (owned by never-deleted

StatisticRecorder).

entry.title: mac: fix GLContext::BackpressureFenceWait crash
entry.content:
This is the crash that should have

a gpu::ImageTransportSurfaceOverlayMacEGL::ApplyBackpressure()

signature.



If the |backpressure_fences| map is empty, the begin() iterator

actually returns the end() iterator. Accessing that is undefined

behaviour as it doesn't point to a valid element. As a result,

the key of the end() iterator can be any value. And if the key

is less than the |fence_id|, this particular code can try to

entry.title: MiracleParameter: Introduce MiracleParameter class
entry.content:
This CL introduces MiracleParameter class, and uses it in

ResourceScheduler as an example.



Unlike FeatureParam, MiracleParameter determines the parameter value

based on the amount of physical memory when the following suffix is used

as a parameter name. If there are no parameter settings that have the

following suffixes, MiracleParameter behaves the same as the

FeatureParam.



- "ForLessThan512MB" for less than 512MB memory devices.

- "For512MBTo1GB" for 512MB to 1GB memory devices.

- "For1GBTo2GB" for 1GB to 2GB memory devices.

- "For2GBTo4GB" for 2GB to 4GB memory devices.

- "For4GBTo8GB" for 4GB to 8GB memory devices.

- "For8GBTo16GB" for 8GB to 16GB memory devices.

- "For16GBAndAbove" for 16GB memory and above devices.



The current implementation of MiracleParameter covers "Plan B" only.





I borrowed many ideas from existing FeatureParam class to write

MiracleParameter.

entry.title: Optimize SpdyHeadersToHttpResponse
entry.content:
SpdyHeadersToHttpResponse creates a header string from an

Http2HeaderBlock and then parses the string to find the offsets of the

names and values. Implement a faster version that keeps track of the

offsets as it creates the string to avoid the expensive parsing step.



Add the HttpResponseHeaders::Builder class which provides an efficient

way to construct an HttpResponseHeaders object from an HTTP version, a

status string and a set of name/value pairs without parsing.



Add SpdyHeadersToHttpResponseHeadersUsingBuilder() function which uses

the new Builder class to convert an Http2HeaderBlock to an

HttpResponseHeaders object.



Add a new feature "SpdyHeadersToHttpResponseUseBuilder" to select the

new implementation at runtime.



Add a new feature "SpdyHeadersToHttpResponseVerifyCorrectness" to

compare the output of the old and new implementations and dump without

crashing if they produce different results.



Add a fuzzer, net_spdy_headers_to_http_response_headers_fuzzer, which

compares the results of the old and new functions and crashes if they

are different.



Add a microbenchmark to compare the performance of the old and new

functions. Results from 100 repetitions on my machine:



SpdyHeadersToHttpResponseHeadersUsingRawString 10817 ns

SpdyHeadersToHttpResponseHeadersUsingBuilders 5946 ns

entry.title: Add ScopedGSignal for managing GLib signal lifetime
entry.content:
Currently, g_signal_connect() is used in //remoting, //ui/gtk,

//net //third_party/webrtc, and //content/browser/accessibility.

In almost all cases, the signal isn't disconnected when receiving

objects are destroyed, which can lead to use-after-frees.



This CL adds ScopedGSignal for safer management of GLib signal

lifetime since proper management of GLib signals is surprisingly

tricky: g_signal_handler_disconnect() should be called when the

signal is no longer needed, but if the sender is deallocated

before disconnecting, a crash will occur in GLib. Therefore we

also need to listen for sender destruction. However, this

creates some more problems since GLib may run the destruction

callback asynchronously after we've disconnected from the signal,

so we also need to carefully remove the destruction callback

in the appropriate places.



Followup CLs will convert usages of g_signal_connect() to

ScopedGSignal, and a presubmit check will be added to prevent

new usages of g_signal_connect().
